<div class="container">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col">
            <article class="full-article">
                
                <div class="kicker"><span class="kicker"><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/news">NEWS</a>
                    &nbsp;|&nbsp;
            <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/news/university">UNIVERSITY</a></span></div>

                <h1>After United Methodists vote against LGBTQ+ inclusion, local churches and Duke Divinity respond</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/06e83b55-38a2-45a4-b332-75fab0d9d374.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="The&#x20;United&#x20;Methodist&#x20;Church&#x20;recently&#x20;voted&#x20;to&#x20;prohibit&#x20;same-sex&#x20;marriages&#x20;in&#x20;their&#x20;churches." class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            The United Methodist Church recently voted to prohibit same-sex marriages in their churches.

                                                             <aside class="photo-caption photo-credit d-block pl-1">
                                    <figcaption class="d-block">
                                                                                    Photo by <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/jake-satisky">Jake Satisky</a> |
                                                                                                                                The Chronicle
                                                                            </figcaption>
                                </aside>
                            
                        </div>
                    </figure>
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/christy-kuesel">Christy Kuesel </a>
                                                             and                     <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/jake-satisky">Jake Satisky</a>
                                        
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">March 18, 2019 | 3:18am EDT</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/03/united-methodists-lgbtq-duke-university-divinity-school-respond-inclusion" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/03/united-methodists-lgbtq-duke-university-divinity-school-respond-inclusion&amp;text=After United Methodists vote against LGBTQ+ inclusion, local churches and Duke Divinity respond" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=After%20United%20Methodists%20vote%20against%20LGBTQ%2B%20inclusion%2C%20local%20churches%20and%20Duke%20Divinity%20respond%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2019%2F03%2Funited-methodists-lgbtq-duke-university-divinity-school-respond-inclusion" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>On the way home from church this past month, Jennifer Ingold Asbill’s seven-year-old daughter asked her why their church had rainbow banners strung up on the railings, visible to anyone driving through the thick fog that blanketed downtown Durham.</p>
<p>How does a parent answer that question? The answer involves faith, politics, community, sexuality—not easy concepts for a child to grasp. So Asbill, pastor for children and pastoral care at Duke Memorial United Methodist Church and Divinity '08, replied as honestly as she could.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>“‘The rainbows were there, this week particularly, because our family and our church family and a lot of our friends believe that when you grow up you can love whoever you want to,’” she told her daughter. “‘We decided as a church that we wanted to put up the rainbow flags to remind everyone that God loves everyone.’”</p>
<p>The past month had been a difficult one for the United Methodist Church. Its General Conference—the global representative body that makes decisions for the entire denomination—voted Feb. 26 to strengthens bans on same-sex marriages and the ordination of LGBTQ+ clergy.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Duke joined 92 Methodist-affiliated colleges in signing a<a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/01/duke-university-joins-methodist-colleges-in-calling-for-inclusion-of-lgbtq-members" target="_blank"> statement in January</a> urging full inclusion of LGBTQ+ individuals in the Methodist Church. <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2018/03/lgbtqia-duke-divinity-students-protest-treatment-issue-list-of-demands" target="_blank">Last March</a>, students at the Divinity School interrupted the Divinity School State of the School address to protest in support of LGBTQ+ issues. Elaine Heath, then-dean of the Divinity School, stepped down in August.</p>
<p>Duke Divinity School is one of the 13 United Methodist seminaries. It receives financial support from the denomination, and the University has had close ties to the congregation.&nbsp;</p>
<p>“Put simply, we will work to ensure that all are welcome to pursue study and preparation for Christian ministry at Duke Divinity School,” Divinity School Dean L. Gregory Jones said in a <a href="https://divinity.duke.edu/news/statement-dean-jones-umc-general-conference" target="_blank">statement</a> following the decision.</p>
<p>Despite the rainbows and support, the aftermath of the General Conference's decision has not been easy for Methodist churches in Durham and Raleigh, including the Divinity School.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Two main plans were proposed. The One Church Plan would have allowed individual churches to determine their marriage policy. The Traditional Plan, which passed the General Conference with 53 percent of the vote, affirms the current bans and amplifies punishments for clergy who marry LGBTQ+ couples.&nbsp;</p>
<p>However, following a <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/14/us/united-methodist-vote.html" target="_blank">further review,</a> at least four ballots were cast by non-voting members. Although the number of these ballots is smaller than the 54-ballot margin by which the vote passed, some church leaders are now calling for a new vote.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Before the vote, the UMC’s Book of Discipline—its constitution—had affirmed the “sacred worth” of all people, yet it also stated that “the practice of homosexuality" is "incompatible with Christian teaching.” The Traditional Plan didn’t change the rules against same-sex marriage or clergy already in place, but it enacted universal punishments for clergy who break the rules regarding homosexuality.</p>
<p>The United Methodist Church is the third largest Christian denomination in the United States, following the Catholic Church and the Southern Baptist Convention. Twelve million Methodists—seven million in America alone—are affected by this decision and face the choice to remain in or leave the church.</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=c4087a59c7" method="post">
                <div class="input-group">
                    <input type="email" name="EMAIL" class="form-control form-control-sm" placeholder="Your email address" />
